@{
    ViewBag.Title = "About";
}
<main aria-labelledby="title" class="space-y-8">
    <section class="space-y-4" aria-labelledby="aboutTitle">
        <h2 id="aboutTitle" class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100">About this Template</h2>
        <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            This starter kit combines <strong>ASP.NET MVC 5 + Web API 2</strong> with modern frontend tooling using
            <strong>Vite</strong>, <strong>Tailwind CSS</strong>, and <strong>Lucide</strong> icons. It is designed to
            give you a secure and scalable baseline with minimal boilerplate.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-slate-600 dark:text-slate-400">
            @ViewBag.Message
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
        <article class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm dark:border-slate-700 dark:bg-slate-900">
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100">Architecture highlights</h3>
            <ul class="list-inside list-disc space-y-1 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
                <li>ASP.NET MVC 5 + ASP.NET Web API 2 project structure.</li>
                <li>Global action filter for per-request CSP nonce generation.</li>
                <li>Asset loading via Vite dev server and production manifest.</li>
            </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm dark:border-slate-700 dark:bg-slate-900">
            <h3 class="mb-2 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100">What to build next</h3>
            <ul class="list-inside list-disc space-y-1 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
                <li>Replace these placeholders with your actual product pages.</li>
                <li>Connect controllers to real domain data and services.</li>
                <li>Use partial views for reusable page sections in <code>Views/Shared</code>.</li>
            </ul>
        </article>
    </section>
    <article class="rounded-xl border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 p-5 shadow-sm dark:border-amber-900 dark:bg-amber-950 md:col-span-2">
        <h3 class="mb-2 text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100">Template tradeoff: unobtrusive validation</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            Traditional ASP.NET MVC client validation is intentionally disabled by default to preserve a Vite-first frontend flow.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            You still keep server-side validation (`ModelState`) as the source of truth, while client UX validation is left
            as an explicit implementation choice.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-inside list-disc space-y-1 mt-3 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            <li>Keep this path if you want modern JS tooling without `jquery.validate` dependencies.</li>
            <li>Restore legacy behavior by re-adding `jQuery.Validation` and `Microsoft.jQuery.Unobtrusive.Validation` plus client scripts.</li>
            <li>Or implement focused validation UX in `Scripts/layout` and form components for better control and fewer transitive packages.</li>
            <li>Server validation still runs on every post and remains the required correctness gate.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>
</main>